column1: 261169;instagram;2018-11-04 16:43:39;FALSE;yesterday was magical. i transferred into this marathon 5 weeks ago. a friend of mine unfortunately became injured during training and offered me her spot. i ran three marathons last year and i needed a break. so since april i cut way back on my mileage and focused on lifting. i had no intention on doing another marathon for a while. then this opportunity happened. i have a hippie type attitude- if the universe presents something to me i feel i should listen. so sure- why not. iâ€™ll run it! i continued my lifting
column2: upped weekly miles & threw in a 17 & 20 mile run before race day. i didnâ€™t know how this would go- i told myself that walking would probably have to happen some and i prayed that all my strength training would carry me through this thing with no injury. yesterdays marathon was so different then my last three. i felt strong. my body didnâ€™t cash out during miles 18-24 like it usually does. i was tired yes but it was different & finished this marathon with a 8 min pr. lifting weights has done so much for me i canâ€™t even explain this. when i focused on only running i was mentally burnt out and found myself with constant pains and several injuries. since lifting i have had no injuries. there is something to this. my body needs it and so does my mind. donâ€™t be afraid to customize your training. my husband said he overheard in the crowd yesterday that only 1% of the population has run a marathon. i wonder if thatâ€™s accurate. running 26 miles is hard- itâ€™s intimidating and can make you very anxious. just doing the training alone is something to be celebrated. we all have careers

column18: upped weekly miles & threw in a 17 & 20 mile run before race day. i didnâ€™t know how this would go- i told myself that walking would probably have to happen some and i prayed that all my strength training would carry me through this thing with no injury. yesterdays marathon was so different then my last three. i felt strong. my body didnâ€™t cash out during miles 18-24 like it usually does. i was tired yes but it was different & finished this marathon with a 8 min pr. lifting weights has done so much for me i canâ€™t even explain this. when i focused on only running i was mentally burnt out and found myself with constant pains and several injuries. since lifting i have had no injuries. there is something to this. my body needs it and so does my mind. donâ€™t be afraid to customize your training. my husband said he overheard in the crowd yesterday that only 1% of the population has run a marathon. i wonder if thatâ€™s accurate. running 26 miles is hard- itâ€™s intimidating and can make you very anxious. just doing the training alone is something to be celebrated. we all have careers

my oldest son just turned 12 and i have been praying a lot lately
column2: asking god how i can connect with him. #asoulsurvivorspiritual i got an answer one morning in the form of a memory.

column1: i remembered when he was little
column3: not old enough to communicate through words but plenty old enough to let me know what he needed. Â i was standing in the kitchen one morning when he woke up and came down the hall and when he entered the kitchen i squealed with delight. i smiled big
column5: ran to him and picked him up in a hug. i was so happy to see him and for some reason that was my response.

column1: the next morning i was asleep when he woke up. i remember this as if it were yesterday. he came into my room
column2: took me by the finger and led me to the kitchen until i was standing where i had been the day before. he squealed
column3: jumped up and down and then hugged my leg. he then turned and walked out of the kitchen and went back to his bedroom. he was gone for a few minutes and while he was gone i knew exactly what he wanted
column4: he wanted to be greeted that same way he had the morning before. when he came back a few minutes later i repeated the same greeting from the previous morning. for a long time this continued and if i was ever asleep when he awoke i was taken back to the kitchen to wait while he came out of his bedroom.

column1: this memory let me know how much austin cares to be with me
column2: even if he won't admit it. he's so independent and gets up all on his own to get ready for school all by himself that i had been using that time to read my scriptures and do a few other things.

column1: i knew instantly that austin cared. he may not express it at this age
column2: but i knew i was missing out on precious time i could be spending with him while he gets ready for school in the mornings. while the things i was doing were good
column3: they could and should be done at a different time so i could spend that time with him.

column1: let your face show each morning what your heart feels.
